In article &lt;69128@sun.uucp&gt; nowicki%rose@Sun.COM (Bill Nowicki) writes:
&gt; In article &lt;16019@shemp.CS.UCLA.EDU&gt;, casey@cs.ucla.edu (Casey Leedom)
&gt;  writes:
&gt; &gt;   Normally this isn't a problem since most of the clients requesting name
&gt; &gt; or address resolution are things like telnet, ftp, etc. and the users
&gt; &gt; invoking those programs eventually type ^C and try again later.  But if
&gt; &gt; the client is sendmail, it doesn't get tired (Sun OS 3.5 and earlier).
&gt; 
&gt; This is not true -- the name server time out was added to sendmail in
&gt; SunOS 3.2, more than two years ago.

  Ah how quickly they forget ...  Bill, don't you remember talking to me
last November when I was trying to get a new sendmail.cf running and came
running to you with this problem?  If I remember right, you were
surprised by several constructs in my sendmail.cf (notably $[...$], name
canonicalization) and discovered that the Sun sendmail.cf didn't use
those and so they had never been tested.  You had to put in two more
timeouts if I remember right and correct a bug that caused the 3.4/3.5
sendmail to core dump with my sendmail.cf ...

  If you want I can send the binaries back to you for your inspection.
(Actually it would be easier for you to pick them up via anonymous ftp
from lll-crg.llnl.gov as the file llnl/named/sun/sun<A NAME="-23"></A><A HREF="#23">[23]</A>.sendmail{,.mx}.

Casey

